 {"id":"br-r37-c1-kpnc8","title":"max_weight_matching tuple direction + matching choice drift from nx","description":"fnx.max_weight_matching returns matched pairs with different tuple directions than nx, and on graphs where multiple equally-optimal matchings exist, picks a different one.

Repro:
  edges = [(0,1),(2,3),(4,5)] (no shared nodes)
  fnx -> {(0,1), (2,3), (4,5)}
  nx  -> {(1,0), (3,2), (5,4)}   <- tuple direction reversed

  edges = [('a','x'),('a','y'),('b','x'),('b','z'),('c','y'),('c','z')]
  fnx -> {('a','y'),('b','x'),('c','z')}
  nx  -> {('a','x'),('b','z'),('c','y')}   <- different valid matching

Drop-in code that compared the matching to a reference {(u,v), ...} pairs broke. Both implementations return correct max-weight matchings, but nx returns each pair (v,u) in a specific direction tied to its DFS-augmenting-path traversal, and the choice between equally-weighted matchings depends on adj-iteration order.

Fix: delegate max_weight_matching to nx via _call_networkx_for_parity (mirrors the existing pattern for articulation_points / find_cliques / cycle_basis).","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-26T14:38:55.459659876Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-26T14:42:53.230854933Z","closed_at":"2026-04-26T14:42:53.228893940Z","close_reason":"done","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
